title: Maxar offering new space-monitoring service to help track objects in orbit
summary: Maxar Technologies has received regulatory approval to use its satellites to monitor the space environment and sell that data commercially.

title: New JWST image reveals full glory of Neptune, its moons, and rings
summary: "It has been three decades since we last saw these faint, dusty rings."

title: Artemis Accords signatories hold first meeting
summary: Nations that have signed the U.S.-led Artemis Accords met in person for the first time Sept. 19 as an initial step to elaborate on the principles for safe and sustainable space exploration.

title: NASA teams prepare for SLS fueling test to inform launch date
summary: As part of continued troubleshooting and seal replacement validation efforts, teams at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida will take the SLS rocket through a Core Stage and Interim Cryogenic Propulsion System (ICPS) fueling test on Wednesday, Sept. 21. NASA officials hope the test will reveal no leaks of the liquid hydrogen (LH2) system, which has so far plagued the agency in all fueling operations where the commodity was loaded onto SLS at the pad.

title: Draft solicitation for national security space launch services expected in early 2023
summary: Brig. Gen. Stephen Purdy said DoD has to approve the NSSL Phase 3 strategy before a draft request for proposals can be released

title: Space Force procurement chief criticizes over-engineered satellite programs
summary: Frank Calvelli: 'The old approach, the seven-year development contracts that we're doing, that has to change'

title: Next batch of OneWeb satellites arrive in India for launch
summary: OneWeb said Sept. 20 its latest batch of 36 broadband satellites has arrived in India ahead of plans to launch them next month on the country's largest rocket.

title: Soyuz MS-22 to loft two Russians and one American to ISS
summary: The Russian federal space agency, Roscosmos, is set to launch three people to the International Space Station (ISS) from Site 31/6 at the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan. Liftoff is scheduled for 13:54:49 UTC on Wednesday, Sept. 21.

title: NASA’s Stakeholder Collaborations Help Inform Moon to Mars Planning
summary: NASA Releases Revised Moon to Mars Objectives

title: NASA set for “kinder, gentler” SLS tanking test
summary: NASA officials say they’re ready to try a new approach to fueling the Space Launch System to prevent the return of leaks that scrubbed an earlier launch attempt even though they are not certain what caused that leak.
